div.p:
solution ¶ Second, we respond that whatever it may be concerning sin, namely if we suppose that they sin, nevertheless the punishment of that sin is reserved to divine judgment alone, and therefore human judgment is excluded from care of this kind. Both because, as appears from what has been said, it is uncertain, indeed it would be impossible to find or discern those whom invincible ignorance cannot excuse from those who are rendered culpable by it. And therefore this distinction is not of human judgment but of divine, because God is the knower and judge of secrets.
32 distinctio, c. erubescant ;
and 2, q. 4, c. consuluisti .
